# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
**Why Greedy doesn't work in 0/1 Knapsack?**
-> Knapsack problem has two values i.e (value, weight). We can't just simply take the items with greater value, coz we've to take the weight into consideration too. The weights of the items are not uniform.
**Why Greedy works in this problem?**
-> Here we don't have the weights of the items. We only have the values. We've to consider the weights of the bars as uniform weights. Hence we can greedily pick the items based on value. 

# 5 Approaches
- Recursion
- Memoization
- Tabulation
- Greedy - Sorting
- Greedy - Heap
# 1. Recursion
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->


# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(2^(N*C))
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(N * C) [Auxiliary Space]
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
private:
    int countBars(int index, int coins, vector<int>& prices) {
        if(index == 0){
            if(coins >= prices[0]) return 1;
            return 0;
        }

        int pick = 0;
        int notPick = countBars(index-1, coins, prices);
        if(coins >= prices[index])pick = 1 + countBars(index-1, coins-prices[index], prices);

        return max(pick, notPick);
    }
public:
    int maxIceCream(vector<int>& costs, int coins) {
        int n = costs.size();
        return countBars(n-1, coins, costs);
    }
};
```

# 2. Memoization
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->


# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(N*C)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(N * C) [DP vector] + O(N * C) [Auxiliary Space]
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
private:
    int countBars(int index, int coins, vector<int>& prices, vector<vector<int>>& dp) {
        if(index == 0){
            if(coins >= prices[0]) return 1;
            return 0;
        }

        if(dp[index][coins] != -1) return dp[index][coins];

        int pick = 0;
        int notPick = countBars(index-1, coins, prices, dp);
        if(coins >= prices[index])pick = 1 + countBars(index-1, coins-prices[index], prices, dp);

        return dp[index][coins] = max(pick, notPick);
    }
public:
    int maxIceCream(vector<int>& costs, int coins) {
        int n = costs.size();
        vector<vector<int>> dp(n, vector<int>(coins+1, -1));
        return countBars(n-1, coins, costs, dp);
    }
};
```

# 3. Tabulation
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->


# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(N*C)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(N * C) [DP vector]
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int maxIceCream(vector<int>& costs, int coins) {
        int n = costs.size();
        vector<vector<int>> dp(n, vector<int>(coins+1, 0));

        for(int i=0;i<=coins;i++){
            if(i >= costs[0]) dp[0][i] = 1;
            else dp[0][i] = 0;
        }

        for(int index = 1; index < n; index++){
            for(int coin = 0; coin <= coins; coin++){
                int pick = 0;
                int notPick = dp[index-1][coin];
                if(coin >= costs[index]) pick = 1 + dp[index-1][coin - costs[index]];

                dp[index][coin] = max(pick, notPick);
            }
        }

        return dp[n-1][coins];
    }
};
```

