# Approach
It's a **greedy** algorithm. **Greedy algorithms are usually paired with sorting**. Hence, we sort the ice-creams and start to sum up their price. The algorithm finishes if we have brought all the ice creams or we have spend all of our coins. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n), where n is the number of ice-creamms (costs.size()) because we need to traverse the vector. However the sorting takes O(n.log(n)) time. Then **the whole algorithm is O(n.log(n))**

- Space complexity: O(1) since we need two additional variables :D


# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int maxIceCream(vector<int>& costs, int coins) {
        sort(costs.begin(), costs.end());

        int coinsSpend = 0;
        int currentIceCream = 0;

        while(currentIceCream < costs.size() && coinsSpend <= coins)
             coinsSpend += costs[currentIceCream++];

        return coinsSpend > coins ? currentIceCream- 1 : currentIceCream;
    }
};
```

