solutions.content:
# Introduction

There are several $O(N \log N)$ solutions for this problem:
* Sort the whole array and choose solution in a greedy-manner
* Make min-heap and extract elements while their sum is less than number of coins (slightly faster, but still need to build heap for the whole array)

However, problem admits two $O(N)$ solutions:
 - Quick-select with $O(1)$ storage requirements; this solution is somewhat elaborated
 - Count-sort with $O(C)$ storage requirements (where $C=10^5$ is the maximum cost of ice-cream bar); this solution is very simple

# Quick-select solution

Let us make three additional observations:
* If sum of $M$ smallest elements is less than number of coins $\Rightarrow$ all $M$ of these elements should be included into solution
* If sum of $M$ smallest elements is larger than number of coins $\Rightarrow$ no other elements will be included into solution
* When partitioning array into elements smaller / larger than pivot, sum of elements smaller than pivot can be computed with minimal computational overhead

Those three observations allow us to construct a quick-select alike algorithm that operates as follows:
* Partition array into elements smaller / larger than pivot, computing sum of elements smaller than pivot
* If sum of smallest elements is larger, than number of coins - forget about larger values and recurse into left segment
* If sum of smallest elements is smaller, than number of coins - subtract that sum from number of coins and recurse into right segment

## Tricks for faster solution

This gives you 100..200ms level solution, my 102ms submission: https://leetcode.com/submissions/detail/759773865/
Achieving lower 100ms requires some tweaking:
* Since there can be up to $10^8$ bars, but costs are limited to $10^5$ => there might be lots of repetitions, thus it is better to partition array into three parts:  [smaller | equal | greater], then skip elements equal to pivot completely with some basic calculations
* A couple of ms can be shaved off by not computing sum once it turns out to be larger, than number of coins (we still need to finish partitioning though).

## Complexity

Time complexity analysis is the same as a regular randomized quick-select algorithm for finding $k$-th smallest element, resulting into $O(N)$ on average.

Space complexity is $O(1)$ if we're allowed to modify input array.


## Solution
Solution with all tricks included:
```
static int speed = [](){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);
    cout.tie(nullptr);
    return 0;
}();

class Solution {
public:
    int solve(int* left, int* right, int coins) {
        int res = 0;
        while (coins && right > left) {
            const int pivot = left[rand() % (right - left)];

			// after end of iteration this should be the last index of values equal to pivot
            auto eq_r = left;
			// after end of iteration this should be the first index of values greater than pivot
            auto gt_l = right;

			// sum of values less than pivot
            int left_sum = 0;
            auto it = left;
			// partition values while accumulating sum of coins with value less than pivot
            while (it != gt_l && left_sum <= coins) {
                int v = *it;
                if (v == pivot) {
                    *it++ = *eq_r++;
                    continue;
                }
                if (v < pivot) {
                    left_sum += v;
                    ++it;
                } else {
                    std::swap(*it, *--gt_l);
                }
            }
			// if sum of coins to the left is grater than target, we still need to partition the rest of values,
			// but can omit maintaining a correct value of the sum
            while (it != gt_l) {
                int v = *it;
                if (v == pivot) {
                    *it++ = *eq_r++;
                    continue;
                }
                if (v < pivot) {
                    ++it;
                } else {
                    std::swap(*it, *--gt_l);
                }
            }

            // Not enough value in smaller coins, need to either add some coins
			// equal to pivot, or even larger coins
            if (left_sum <= coins) {
                coins -= left_sum;
                int eq_cnt = coins / pivot;
                int real_eq = eq_r - left;

				// need at least as much coins valued as pivot as we have
                if (eq_cnt >= real_eq) {
                    coins -= real_eq * pivot;
                    res += gt_l - left;
                    if (coins <= pivot) {
                        coins = 0;
                        break;
                    }
                    left = gt_l;
                    continue;
                }
				// we have enough pivot-valued coins to fullfill the target
                res += (gt_l - eq_r) + eq_cnt;
                coins = 0;
                break;
            }
			// Sum of coins with value less than pivot is larger than target,
			// so we need to select from them.
			// Since we kept coins equal to the pivot at the left side of the
			// array, we need to skip them
            left = eq_r;
            right = gt_l;
        }
        return res;
    }

    int maxIceCream(vector<int>& costs, int coins) {
        auto it = solve(costs.data(), costs.data() + costs.size(), coins);
        return it;
    }
};
```

# Count-sort solution:

Another option for achieving $O(N)$ is to exploit the upper limit on cost being just $C=10^5$.

This allows to sort costs of ice-cream bars using count sort, followed by computing number of ice-cream bars boy can buy using given number of coins.

This allows one to get a simple solution with $O(N) + O(C)$ compute complexity and $O(C)$ memory consumption.

```
class Solution {
public:
    int maxIceCream(vector<int>& costs, int coins) {
        constexpr int MAX_COST = 100001;
        int cnt[MAX_COST] = {0};
        for (auto& c: costs) {
            ++cnt[c];
