# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
 counts the frequency of each cost, calculates the maximum number of ice cream cones that can be bought for each cost, and updates the answer accordingly. The intuition is to iterate through the costs, considering the available budget and the frequency of each cost, to determine the maximum number of ice cream cones that can be bought.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The code aims to find the maximum number of ice cream cones that can be bought within the given budget (coins).

It first finds the maximum cost among all the ice cream cones using the max_element function from the STL. This helps determine the maximum size needed for the vector v used later.

It initializes a vector v of size max_no + 1, where max_no is the maximum cost. This vector will be used to count the frequency of each cost in the costs vector.

The code then iterates through the costs vector and increments the corresponding index in v to count the occurrences of each cost.

Next, the code initializes a variable ans to keep track of the maximum number of ice cream cones that can be bought.

It then iterates through the v vector, starting from index 1, which represents the minimum cost. For each cost, it calculates the maximum number of ice cream cones that can be bought by dividing the remaining coins by the current cost (coins/i).

The code then takes the minimum value between the calculated maximum number of ice cream cones (can_buy) and the frequency of the current cost (v[i]). This ensures that we don't exceed the available frequency or the budget.

It adds the calculated minimum value to the ans variable to update the maximum number of ice cream cones that can be bought.

Finally, the code subtracts the cost of the bought ice cream cones (temp * i) from the coins variable.

The process continues for all costs in the v vector.

Once the iterations are complete, the code returns the maximum number of ice cream cones that can be bought (ans).
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
     O(n)

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
     O(max_no)

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int maxIceCream(vector<int>& costs, int coins) {

      int max_no = *max_element(costs.begin(),costs.end());
      vector<int> v(max_no+1);
      for(auto it:costs){
          v[it]++;
      }
      int ans = 0;
      for(int i  = 1;i<v.size();i++){
          int can_buy = coins/i;
          int temp = min(can_buy,v[i]);
          ans += temp;
          coins -= (temp * i);

      }
      return ans;

    }
};
```

