# Naive approach
We know we have to maximise the number of ice creams to buy, so initial thought is to simply sort he array and then iterate over the numbers in order subtracting the cost from couns.

```
var maxIceCream = function(costs, coins) {
    costs = costs.sort((a, b) => a - b)
    let res = 0

    for (let i = 0; i < costs.length; i++) {
        coins = coins - costs[i]
        if (coins > -1) {
            res++
        } else {
            return res
        }
    }
    return res
};
```
But this is not optimal, since sorting can take quite some time.
- Time complexity: O(N log N) due to sorting. 
    - In case input array has small number of items, this could run in O(n^2) time.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: This should be O(log N) again due to sorting
    - JS sort is somewhat optimized for smaller numbers when it should use O(1) space 
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Optimized
Let's create a helping array where we store the frequiency or count of ice creams of the same cost (`countSort`). The index will be their cost, and the value will be their count. The array has to be of the size of biggest cost of ice cream.

Example:
```
[1,3,2,4,1]
```

would have a frequency array like:
```
[0, 2, 1, 1, 1]
```

After we have that, we loop through frequency array. We start from index 1, since inde 0 will always have value 0 (but it's possible to do some tweaks here to start from 0th index if you are really stretched for space but I find this approach more clean).

We can skip any step where frequency value is 0.
In case we come across a point where number of couns we have is less than the cost, we came to a point where we can't buy more ice cream so stop the itertion and return the result.

In case we can still buy more ice cream we calculate the result. 
First find out how many icecreams of `cost` we can pick with our current coins. Then subtract that value from coins and increase our result with it.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(N), we do have two loops, but they are not nested, so it's linear time.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(N), due to using of an array for extra space
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
/**
 * @param {number[]} costs
 * @param {number} coins
 * @return {number}
 */
var maxIceCream = function(costs, coins) {
    let max = Math.max(...costs)
    let countSort = Array(max + 1).fill(0)
    let res = 0

    for (let i of costs) {
        countSort[i]++
    }

    for (let cost = 1; cost <= max; cost++) {
        if (!countSort[cost]) continue;

        // not enough money to buy even a single ice cream
        if (coins < cost) break;

        let count = Math.min(countSort[cost], Math.floor(coins / cost))
        coins -= cost * count;
        res += count

    }

    return res
};
```

